  "body": "Helm currently imports k8s.io/kubernetes in a few places. At time of writing:\r\n```\r\npkg/kube/wait.go\r\n32:     deploymentutil \"k8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/controller/deployment/util\"\r\n\r\npkg/kube/client.go\r\n58:     \"k8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/api/legacyscheme\"\r\n59:     \"k8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/apis/core\"\r\n60:     \"k8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/kubectl/cmd/get\"\r\n61:     cmdutil \"k8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/kubectl/cmd/util\"\r\n62:     \"k8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/kubectl/validation\"\r\n\r\npkg/kube/client_test.go\r\n37:     cmdtesting \"k8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/kubectl/cmd/testing\"\r\n38:     kubectlscheme \"k8s.io/kubernetes/pkg/kubectl/scheme\r\n```\r\n\r\nKubernetes intentionally ships a broken `go.mod` file to discourage people from depending on k8s.io/kubernetes (see https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/79384). As a result, in order to depend on helm, we must go through major hacks to get go modules working.\r\n\r\nIs it feasible to drop this dependency?\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/79384#issuecomment-538740756 indicates it may be possible to move the controller library out of k8s.io/kubernetes, and I think the `api` and `kubectl` ones can already use `k8s.io/api` and `k8s.io/kubectl`\r\n",
